node.text:
You know Barbie, but have you met… Barbie? 💖 That’s right; Barbie Roberts meets Barbie Roberts, and they have more in common than just their name! The two became fast friends and chose nicknames inspired by their hometowns – Malibu and Brooklyn – to better differentiate when they’re together.
 
Gather your kids and join the two friends in this dorm room unboxing to get to know #Barbie “Brooklyn” Roberts!

Dreams take vision. Pursuing them takes courage. All girls deserve both.

In time for #HispanicHeritageMonth, the Barbie Dream Gap Project is proud to announce a new, year-long partnership with @Latinitas – one of just a few bilingual STEAM education nonprofits nationwide, dedicated to empowering girls to make their mark in media and tech.

The donation will give $50,000 toward programs for girls to explore #STEAM and digital media activities around wellness, design, entrepreneurialism, filmmaking, coding and more, with opportunities taking place both virtually and in-person.

To learn more about The Dream Gap and what you can do to get involved, visit barbie.com/dreamgap.

node.text:
The stories we tell have the power to create a more inclusive world. 📓 In celebration of Hispanic Heritage Month, Barbie is proud to gift Julia Alvarez a one-of-a-kind doll in her likeness, and to honor her legacy in helping to pave the way for more girls to share their stories.
Julia Alvarez is an award-winning Dominican-American writer, educator, and activist, whose vast body of work explores multicultural themes as they relate to children and adults alike. For decades, she has worked to promote literacy as a tool to overcome generational poverty, and remained an outspoken advocate for peace between the Dominican Republic and Haiti.

node.text: There’s nothing more powerful than using your voice! 🎙️💃 This Hispanic Heritage Month, Barbie is thrilled to honor the memory of the inimitable “Queen of Salsa,” Celia Cruz, with a one-of-a-kind doll in her likeness. As a stage performer, on-screen actor, and recording artist who succeeded in a male-dominated music scene, Celia Cruz is also known as the “Latin Triple Threat.” Her long and storied career serves as endless inspiration for aspiring musicians, and through the Celia Cruz Foundation, her legacy continues to provide scholarships for young Latino students.

node.text: For three years, the Barbie Día de Muertos series has paid tribute to the Mexican festival of remembrance and its customs, symbols and rituals. Now for the first time ever, Barbie introduces a collectible Ken doll to the series. Wearing a charro-inspired look featuring a sarape and embroidered shirt, with face painted in a striking calavera design, this doll is the perfect gift for all who celebrate.

node.text: When we celebrate those we’ve lost, their memories live on in us forever. Now in its third year, the Barbie Día De Muertos series continues to honor the rich culture and symbolism of the Mexican festival of remembrance, and for the first time ever is joined by a collectible Ken doll to be treasured as a new addition to your family traditions.
